Okay, I've read the posts, slogged through the emails, and I'm ready to make some conclusions. And before anyone starts looking for bias, I play on Luclin and I don't know any of the people involved in this whole Conquest business. I'm as impartial to this issue as you can get but frankly I've gotten so offended from a professional point of view that I'm saying something about it.<br>
<br>
VI: What the hell kind of Mickey Mouse operation are you running?<br>
<br>
I'm not speaking from a Customer Service point of view, but from a SOFTWARE ENGINEERING point of view. STOP RIGHT THERE, folks, I did NOT say &quot;programming&quot;. I said SOFTWARE ENGINERING. As in process control. Architectural design documents. Detailed design documents. Unit Testing. Integration testing, with dedicated testing staff (one person does NOT comprise a STAFF, dammit!) Frankly I'm getting tired of seeing paying customers being penalized for YOUR mistakes. For YOUR rush to bring a product to market. <br>
<br>
Do you know what any of the things I've mentioned above are, VI? Do you have any kind of requirements specification? Because if you don't, how can your developers possibly know what to develop for each other? Have you ever heard of the Unified Modeling Language and what it's used for? Do you actually USE black- and white-box testing? You know, folks, you're DAMN lucky. Companies in other industries get SUED when their products fail like yours. And they DAMN SURE don't penalize their customers for using workarounds to deal with software bugs. How about this for a scary thought: having to make ABSOLUTELY SURE that your software is SO robust, SO well designed, that it MUST WORK all the time, in every conceivable situation, because when your customer really, really needs it, it will be when other people are trying to KILL them. I've been there, folks. Have you ever heard of MIL-STD-498? Download it and READ IT. It details the software development ENGINEERING PROCESS. Because it's pretty DAMNED obvious that you folks don't know the first thing about engineering a proper software product.<br>
<br>
Here's a hint: if you don't know the difference between a SOFTWARE ENGINEER and a PROGRAMMER, you have a LONG way to go. Which kind do YOU employ? I'll bet I can guess.<br>
<br>
/rant off<br>
<br>
